ditors’ marks from Verdi’s own notations while remaining clear enough for use in performance. The introduction to each score discusses the work’s sources, composition, and performance history, as well as performance practices, instrumentation, and problems of notation. The newest editions of the study scores examine two of Verdi’s three-act operas: La traviata and Rigoletto.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aOperasvLibrettos. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  agiuseppe verdi, opera, music, performing arts, lecher, court jester, curse, beauty, romance, seduction, love, assassination, cuckold, sexuality, vengeance, revenge, honor, abduction, mistress, courtiers, palace, royalty, nobility, performance, unfaithful, reception, murder, daughter, stabbing, violence, retribution, fate, supernatural, tragedy, nonfiction.1 aChusid, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226521633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226521633/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles